Impact of Discount on Profit%¶

In [298]:
x=data['Sales']
y=data['Profit']
b=[]
for j in range(len(x)):
    q=round(y[j]*100/(x[j]-y[j]),2)
    b.append(q)
data['Profit%']=b
In [299]:
st.shapiro(data['Profit%'])
Out[299]:
ShapiroResult(statistic=0.9671892523765564, pvalue=1.1462621438177004e-42)
In [300]:
st.shapiro(data['Discount Amt'])
Out[300]:
ShapiroResult(statistic=0.10927116870880127, pvalue=0.0)
In [301]:
st.levene(data['Discount Amt'],data['Profit%'])
Out[301]:
LeveneResult(statistic=42.96100965156526, pvalue=5.72048573689252e-11)
In [302]:
#As discount and profit% do not follow normal distribution -> Non-Parametric
st.spearmanr(data['Discount Amt'],data['Profit%'])
Out[302]:
SpearmanrResult(correlation=-0.007070027383107432, pvalue=0.4797460735315925)
In [303]:
from matplotlib import style
style.use('classic')
sn.scatterplot(data['Discount Amt'], data['Profit%'])
Out[303]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Discount Amt', ylabel='Profit%'>

As the resultant correlation coefficient is negative, we can say that there is weak negative correlation between discount & profit% and discount is negatively affecting the profit% i.e, if we increase discounts then profit% slightly decreases

In [304]:
dx = data.groupby('Region').agg({'Sales':'sum','Profit':'sum','Quantity':'sum','Discount Amt':'sum'}).reset_index()
# data.groupby('Region').agg({'Sales':'sum'}).reset_index()

dx['% sales'] = dx['Sales']/sum(dx['Sales'])
dx['% profit'] = dx['Profit']/sum(dx['Profit'])
dx['% quantity'] = dx['Quantity']/sum(dx['Quantity'])
dx['% discount'] = dx['Discount Amt']/sum(dx['Discount Amt'])
# dx['% sales'] = dx['Sales']/sum(dx['Sales'])
dx = dx[['Region','% sales','% profit','% quantity']]
In [305]:
dx.plot(x="Region", y=["% sales", "% profit", "% quantity"], kind="bar")
Out[305]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Region'>

Predictive analytics¶

As the data contains various metrics related to sales like orders, categories, sub categories, sales etc amd the quantity is a continuous metric, In this scenario we are taking the quantity as the target variable and predict it using various features. This is clearly a regression problem¶

Evaluating the model using MAE(Mean Average Error), MSE(Mean Squared Error), (Coefficient of Determination)R2, MAPE(Mean Absolute Percentage Error)¶

MAE: It is the mean of the errors between between the actual and predicted values¶

MSE: It is the mean of the squares of difference between the actual and predicted values¶

R2-Score: It is a metric representing the determination coefficient, it usually ranges between 0 and 1 where 1 being the heighest accuracy¶

MAPE: It is the percentage of mean of absolute errors between the actual and predicted values¶

In [350]:
print('MAE:', mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred))
print('MSE:', mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
print('R2:', r2_score(y_test, y_pred))
print('MAPE:', mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_test, y_pred))

MAE: 1.310510279134609
MSE: 2.310510279134609
R2: 0.61512222069806706
MAPE: 0.3207320032925795

This shows that the model is performing with an avccuracy close to 68% as the mape score is 0.32 i.e 32% error¶
